                <img src="@Model.ImageURL" alt="@Model.BlogHeading" title="@Model.BlogHeading" onerror="this.onerror=null; this.src='@Url.Content("~/images/default.jpg")';" />
                <div class="upcoming-bikes-details-text">
                    <p><i class="fa fa-calendar"></i> @Model.Date?.ToString("d MMM yyyy")</p>
                    @* <p>@ViewBag.TWNews.NewsSummary</p> *@
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="latest-bikes-details-content">

                <p><span class="font-weight-700">Written by:</span> BikeCarHub Editorial Team</p>
                <p><span class="font-weight-700">Published on:</span> 26th June 2025</p>

                <div class="div-line"></div>
                <h2 class="subheading">Introduction</h2>

                <p>@Html.Raw(@Model.BlogSummary.Replace("\n", "<br>"))</p>

                <div class="div-line"></div>

                <h2 class="subheading">1. Design & Positioning</h2>

                <h3 class="subheading">Kia Sonet</h3>
                <p>Modern, bold, and tech-forward. Facelifted in December 2023, it features a sharper "tiger-nose" grille, jewel-cut LED headlamps, and a sportier rear profile. Its wide color palette and optional panoramic sunroof add to its youthful vibe.</p>

                <h3 class="subheading">Hyundai Venue</h3>
                <p>Revised in 2022, the Venue focuses on urban sophistication. It boasts split LED DRLs connected to a sleek grille, along with a fresh LED tail lamp bar—all complemented by rugged cladding, ambient lighting, and a hatchback-like rear that blends form with function.</p>

                <div class="div-line"></div>
                <h2 class="subheading">2. Powertrains & Performance</h2>
                <p>Both SUVs share the same trio of engines, transmissions, fuel-efficiency ratings, and displacement stats, all rooted in the K-platform architecture.</p>

                <h3 class="subheading">Engine Lineup:</h3>
                <div style="overflow-x: auto;">
                    <table class="comparison-table-content">
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th class="text-center">Engine Variant</th>
                                <th class="text-center">Kia Sonet</th>
                                <th class="text-center">Hyundai Venue</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr class="compare-head-text">
                                <td>1.2L NA Petrol</td>
                                <td>1,197cc, 82PS, ~115Nm</td>
                                <td>1,197cc, 83PS, 114Nm</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>1.0L Turbo Petrol</td>
                                <td>998cc T-GDi, 120PS, 172Nm</td>
                                <td>998cc T-GDi, 118PS, 172Nm</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr class="compare-head-text">
                                <td>1.5L Diesel</td>
                                <td>1,493cc CRDi, 114PS, 250Nm</td>
                                <td>1,493cc CRDi, 114PS, 250Nm</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <h3 class="subheading">Transmissions:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Both offer 5-speed MT on NA petrol, 6-speed MT on turbo and diesel, a 7-speed DCT with paddle shifters for turbo petrol, and Hyundai's 6-speed torque converter for turbo and diesel.</li>
                    <li>Sonet includes sand/mud/wet traction modes across variants.</li>
                    <li>Venue delivers driving modes (Eco/Normal/Sport) and Bluelink's connected car ecosystem.</li>
                </ul>

               
                    <p><span class="font-weight-700">Performance Insight:</span> Both SUVs feel nearly identical in drive, thanks to shared mechanicals, but Sonet leans sporty with paddle shifters and traction modes—it's for the enthusiastic driver, while Venue leans slightly more versatile for daily urban use.</p>
               

                <div class="div-line"></div>
                <h2 class="subheading">3. Fuel Economy (ARAI)</h2>
                <p>Claimed numbers across engines are also matched:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">1.2L petrol:</span> ~18-19 kmpl</li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">1.0L turbo petrol:</span> ~18.4 kmpl</li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">1.5L diesel:</span> ~24 kmpl</li>
                </ul>

                
                    <p><span class="font-weight-700">Verdict:</span> Expect fuel numbers within a narrow band, with about 0.5 kmpl variance depending on transmission. Diesel leads the field significantly.</p>
                

                <div class="div-line"></div>
                <h2 class="subheading">4. Exterior Dimensions & Practicality</h2>
                <p>Both SUVs are twins in size, but the Sonet wins in cargo room:</p>

                <div style="overflow-x: auto;">
                    <table class="comparison-table-content">
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th class="text-center">Dimension</th>
                                <th class="text-center">Kia Sonet</th>
                                <th class="text-center">Hyundai Venue</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr class="compare-head-text">
                                <td>Length × Width × Height</td>
                                <td>3,995 × 1,790 ×1,642mm</td>
                                <td>3,995 × 1,770 × 1,617mm</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Wheelbase</td>
                                <td>2,500mm</td>
                                <td>2,500mm</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr class="compare-head-text">
                                <td>Ground Clearance</td>
                                <td>~205mm</td>
                                <td>~195mm</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Boot Space</td>
                                <td>385L</td>
                                <td>350L</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr class="compare-head-text">
                                <td>Fuel Tank</td>
                                <td>45L</td>
                                <td>45L</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <div class="verdict-box">
                    <p><span class="font-weight-700">Insights:</span></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Boot space: Sonet offers 35L more—helpful for travel gear.</li>
                        <li>Ground clearance: Sonet is ~10mm higher—slightly better for rough roads.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="div-line"></div>
                <h2 class="subheading">5. Safety & Driver Assistance Tech</h2>
                <p>Both SUVs share robust active and passive safety tech:</p>

                <h3 class="subheading">Kia Sonet:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>6-airbags, ABS with EBD, ESC, HAC, VSM, ESS</li>
                    <li>Blind View Monitor (BVM), 360° camera, hill-assist</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="subheading">Hyundai Venue:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>6-airbags, ESC, HAC, VSM, tyre-pressure monitoring, hill-start assist</li>
                    <li>Rear camera/sensors, dash cams on N Line, Bluelink SOS/emergency, electro-chromatic IRVM</li>
                    <li>Venue Knight and N Line even offer ADAS (FCA, LDW, LKA, HBA, etc.) in top trims</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="verdict-box">
                    <p><span class="font-weight-700">Edge in Safety:</span></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Sonet leads with BVM and 360° camera.</li>
                        <li>Venue counters with advanced telematics (SOS), dash cam, and lane-level ADAS in flagship trims.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="div-line"></div>
                <h2 class="subheading">6. Interior & Convenience Features</h2>

                <h3 class="subheading">Kia Sonet:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>8″ or 10.25″ touchscreen with UVO connected car (OTA updates, Alexa), paired with 10.25″ digital cluster</li>
                    <li>Ventilated front seats, wireless charger, panoramic sunroof, pure air purifier, Bose 7-speaker audio</li>
                    <li>Traction modes, paddle-shifters, and premium materials in higher trims</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="subheading">Hyundai Venue:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>8″/10.25″ touchscreen with Bluelink (60+ features), voice command, over-the-air updates</li>
                    <li>Ambient lighting, air purifier, powered driver's seat, sunroof, wireless charging, dual-cam dash-cam in N Line, Bose audio in select trims</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="verdict-box">
                    <p>
                        <span class="font-weight-700">Takeaway:</span><br>
                        Sonet delivers a bold, tech-lux feel with digital instruments, while Venue doubles down on convenience and smart connected services via Bluelink.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div class="div-line"></div>
                <h2 class="subheading">7. Ride Quality & Driving Impressions</h2>
                <p>Shared platform yields similar ride frameworks:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Sonet:</span> Slightly firmer suspension for sharper handling; traction modes and paddle-shifts add involvement</li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Venue:</span> Tuned for urban comfort; DCT is slick though may occasional jerk; steering is light at low speeds, firm at highways</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="verdict-box">
                    <p>
                        <span class="font-weight-700">Summary:</span><br>
                        Sonet is for the spirited driver; Venue is for smooth daily driving with convenience.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div class="div-line"></div>
                <h2 class="subheading">8. Pricing & Variants</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Kia Sonet:</span> ₹8.00L -- ₹15.74L ex-showroom across petrol/diesel, MT/AT/DCT/iMT trims</li>
                    <li><span class="font-weight-700">Hyundai Venue:</span> ₹7.94L -- ₹13.62L for standard; N Line at ₹12.14L+; diesel peaks around ₹16.20L</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="verdict-box">
                    <p>
                        <span class="font-weight-700">Value Insight:</span><br>
                        Venue offers slightly lower entry-level pricing and connected tech, while Sonet charges extra for premium gear in higher trims.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div class="div-line"></div>
                <h2 class="subheading">9. Ownership Experience & After-Sales</h2>

                <h3 class="subheading">Kia Sonet:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>High owner satisfaction due to features and design.</li>
                    <li>UVO helps with over-the-air updates.</li>
                    <li>Good service network but slightly fewer centers than Hyundai.</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="subheading">Hyundai Venue:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Bluelink support and strong service infrastructure.</li>
                    <li>Lower service costs in entry trims.</li>
                    <li>Dash cams in N Line offer safety advantages.</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="div-line"></div>
                <h2 class="subheading">10. Feature Comparison Table</h2>
                <div style="overflow-x: auto;">
                    <table class="comparison-table-content">
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th class="text-center">Category</th>
                                <th class="text-center">Kia Sonet</th>
                                <th class="text-center">Hyundai Venue</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr class="compare-head-text">
                                <td>Boot Space</td>
                                <td>385L (+35L)</td>
                                <td>350L</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Ground Clearance</td>
                                <td>~205mm</td>
                                <td>~195mm</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr class="compare-head-text">
                                <td>Infotainment</td>
                                <td>10.25″ touchscreen + UVO, Alexa, OTA updates</td>
                                <td>10.25″ touchscreen + Bluelink, voice/SOS, OTA</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Driver Display</td>
                                <td>10.25″ digital cluster</td>
                                <td>Digital instrument cluster</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr class="compare-head-text">
                                <td>Audio System</td>
                                <td>Bose 7-speaker system</td>
                                <td>Bose available in higher trims</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Sunroof</td>
                                <td>Panoramic</td>
                                <td>Standard electric sunroof in top trims</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr class="compare-head-text">
                                <td>Safety Tech</td>
                                <td>360° camera, BVM, ESC, HAC</td>
                                <td>ESC, HAC, dash cam, BL, SOS, ADAS on flagship</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Drive Modes</td>
                                <td>Sand/Mud/Wet traction modes</td>
                                <td>Eco/Normal/Sport drive modes</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr class="compare-head-text">
                                <td>Transmission Options</td>
                                <td>MT/AT/DCT</td>
                                <td>MT/DCT, iMT available</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td>Price Range (₹ Lakh)</td>
                                <td>8.00 -- 15.74</td>
                                <td>7.94 -- 16.20</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>

                <div class="div-line"></div>
                <h2 class="subheading">Final Verdict</h2>

                <h3 class="subheading">Choose Kia Sonet if:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>You prioritize <span class="font-weight-700">maximum boot space</span> and <span class="font-weight-700">higher ground clearance</span></li>
                    <li>Tech-forward features like a <span class="font-weight-700">panoramic sunroof</span>, <span class="font-weight-700">digital cluster</span>, <span class="font-weight-700">paddle shifters</span>, and <span class="font-weight-700">premium Bose audio</span> matter</li>
                    <li>You prefer a more <span class="font-weight-700">engaging drive</span> with traction modes and sporty tuning</li>
                </ul>

                <h3 class="subheading">Choose Hyundai Venue if:</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>You value <span class="font-weight-700">superior connectivity</span> with Bluelink's 60+ functions (SOS, remote control, voice, OTA)</li>
                    <li>You desire convenience features like <span class="font-weight-700">dual-cam dash-cams</span>, <span class="font-weight-700">powered driver seat</span>, and ambient enhancements</li>
                    <li>You seek a <span class="font-weight-700">smooth daily ride</span>, with slightly better entry pricing</li>
                </ul>

                <div class="verdict-box">
                    <p><span class="font-weight-700">Summary Takeaways:</span></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><span class="font-weight-700">Identical engines, nearly identical mechanicals</span>—fuel economy, sizes, and performance align closely.</li>
                        <li><span class="font-weight-700">Sonet stands out</span> on fun-factor, tech-richness, and cargo practicality.</li>
                        <li><span class="font-weight-700">Venue shines</span> on connected services, comfort, and inclusive convenience.</li>
                        <li>Budget range overlaps—choose based on your priorities: <span class="font-weight-700">space & fun vs connectivity & ride comfort</span>.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

               
            
